      {
         "id": "SECTION_introduction",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Introduction\n\nThis text examines two calendrical systems used in Mesoamerica (*Abya Yala*) (Figure 1)  prior to colonization (<htcite0>; <htcite1>; <htcite2>):\n- *Tzolkin* (260 dias).\n- *Haab* (365 dias).\n\nTo enhance understanding, we will analyze these calendars using our contemporary numerical system. A subsequent text will revisit them using Indigenous numerical frameworks.\n\nBefore proceeding, consider:",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "ceffba8a-43be-4de3-a5c8-27cdf81311b1",
                     "text": "Puente, Francisco Barriga",
                     "page": "pp. 35",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2020",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "ad11b3b2-8cdf-4d71-9cb7-2ac241850945",
                     "text": "Casares Contreras, Orlando & Cetina, José & Cabrera, Venus Sarahí.",
                     "page": "pp. 33 - 34",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2022",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "eca99877-c520-4569-a71c-0a5b3dd77dc4",
                     "text": "Casares Contreras, Orlando & Cetina, José & Cabrera, Venus Sarahí.",
                     "page": "pp. 33 - 34",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2022",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 1: On Social Organization</b><br /><br />Did Mesoamerican Indigenous peoples also employ week-like systems?</div></div></center>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p class=\"desc\"><img id=\"imgMA\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgMA', '0%')\" src=\"images/Mapswire/mapswire-continent_na-printable-map-north-america-robinson-269_mesoamerica2.jpg\" class=\"imgcenter\"/>Figure 1: Mesoamerica map per Creamer’s research (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('2d720f02-051c-4469-b425-7d020f2c2f9b'); return false;\">Creamer, W., pp. 37 - 55, <htdate0></a>)</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_groups",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Indigenous Periods\n\nSince the indigenous peoples of Mesoamerica (*Abya Yala*) used a vigesimal system, we cannot directly apply concepts from cultures that employed a decimal system. To accurately interpret their texts, we must first understand what they explicitly state.\n\nIndigenous groups used the following time cycles shorter than a year (<htcite0>; <htcite1>; <htcite2>):\n\n- *k'in'*: Equivalent to one day.\n- *winal*: A period of 20 days.\n- *tun*: 360 days.\n\nWith the exception of the *k'in* (one day), none of these cycles align with the months and years we use today, nor with the *Tzolkin* cycle (260 days) or the solar year (365 days). Thus, a deeper study of these calendars is necessary.\n\n#### *Tzolkin*\n\nThe *Tzolkin* is a sacred calendar still in use in some regions of Guatemala. It consists of 13 groups of 20 days, with each day representing the name of a Mayan deity (<htcite3>).\n\nBefore proceeding, let us verify the grouping of this calendar:",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "ceffba8a-43be-4de3-a5c8-27cdf81311b1",
                     "text": "Puente, Francisco Barriga",
                     "page": "pp. 107",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2020",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "ad11b3b2-8cdf-4d71-9cb7-2ac241850945",
                     "text": "Casares Contreras, Orlando & Cetina, José & Cabrera, Venus Sarahí.",
                     "page": "pp. 34",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2022",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "eca99877-c520-4569-a71c-0a5b3dd77dc4",
                     "text": "Casares Contreras, Orlando & Cetina, José & Cabrera, Venus Sarahí.",
                     "page": "pp. 34",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2022",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "ced67eaf-7378-4589-9166-07f799969e3e",
                     "text": "Catepillán, Ximena",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2023",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p style=\"text-align=center\"><center>Multiplying by: <input class=\"ordercheck\" type=\"checkbox\" id=\"1\" /> Ones <input class=\"ordercheck\" type=\"checkbox\" id=\"2\" /> Tens</center></p><p style=\"text-align=center\"><center>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <span class=\"multexample1\" id=\"mmtc1\">1</span><span class=\"multexample1\" id=\"mmtc1\">3</span> <br />× &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<span class=\"multexample1\" id=\"mmbc2\">2</span><span class=\"multexample1\" id=\"mmbc1\">0</span><br />_________<br /></span>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <span class=\"multexample1\" id=\"mmptrc2\">0</span><span class=\"multexample1\" id=\"mmptrc1\">0</span><br />+&nbsp;&nbsp; <span class=\"multexample1\" id=\"mmpbrc2\">26</span><span class=\"multexample1\" id=\"mmpbrc1\">0</span><br />_________<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<span class=\"multexample1\" id=\"mmrc3\">2</span><span class=\"multexample1\" id=\"mmrc2\">6</span><span class=\"multexample1\" id=\"mmrc1\">0 </span></center></p><p class=\"desc\">Calculation 1: Multiplying 20 by 13.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "Having confirmed the count of 260 days, we can examine how days are identified in this calendar. According to Dr. Ximena Catepillán (<htcite0>):\n- The first day of the year is *1 imix*.\n- The last day of the year is *13 ahau*.\n- There are 20 consecutive periods of 13 days.",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "ced67eaf-7378-4589-9166-07f799969e3e",
                     "text": "Catepillán, Ximena",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2023",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p>Below, we highlight today’s date, <span id=\"tzolkin_day\"></span>, in the <i>Tzolkin</i> calendar:</p><p id=\"tzolkin_calendar\" class=\"tableTen\"></p><p class=\"desc\">Table 1: The <i>Tzolkin</i> calendar.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "Since this calendar is not part of daily use today, identifying dates within it can be confusing. To aid understanding, we have mapped the *Tzolkin* onto the Gregorian calendar for the current year (Table 2).\n\nNote that because the *Tzolkin* has 260 days, its current cycle began on <span id=\"tzolkinBegin\"></span>, and will end on <span id=\"tzolkinEnd\"></span>, according to the Gregorian calendar:",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><table id=\"gregorian_calendar\" class=\"tableTen\"></table></p><p class=\"desc\">Table 2: <i>Tzolkin</i> calendar mapped to the current month.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "#### *Haab*\n\nThe *Haab* (or *Ha:b*) is the Mayan civil calendar. Its duration varied throughout history (<htcite0>; <htcite1>). Between <htdate0> and <htdate1>, it comprised 360 days (**Calculation 2**), divided into 20 periods of 18 days:",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "ad11b3b2-8cdf-4d71-9cb7-2ac241850945",
                     "text": "Casares Contreras, Orlando & Cetina, José & Cabrera, Venus Sarahí.",
                     "page": "pp. 33 - 34",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2022",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "eca99877-c520-4569-a71c-0a5b3dd77dc4",
                     "text": "Casares Contreras, Orlando & Cetina, José & Cabrera, Venus Sarahí.",
                     "page": "pp. 33 - 34",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2022",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": [
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "-300",
                     "month": "-1",
                     "day": "-1"
                  },
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "300",
                     "month": "-1",
                     "day": "-1"
                  }
               ],
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p style=\"text-align=center\"><center>Multiply by: <input class=\"ordercheck\" type=\"checkbox\" id=\"3\" /> Ones <input class=\"ordercheck\" type=\"checkbox\" id=\"4\" /> Tens</center></p><p style=\"text-align=center\"><center>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <span class=\"multexample1\" id=\"mmtc4\">1</span><span class=\"multexample1\" id=\"mmtc3\">8</span> <br />× &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<span class=\"multexample1\" id=\"mmbc4\">2</span><span class=\"multexample1\" id=\"mmbc3\">0</span><br />_________<br /></span>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <span class=\"multexample1\" id=\"mmptrc4\">0</span><span class=\"multexample1\" id=\"mmptrc3\">0</span><br />+&nbsp;&nbsp; <span class=\"multexample1\" id=\"mmpbrc4\">36</span><span class=\"multexample1\" id=\"mmpbrc3\">0</span><br />_________<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<span class=\"multexample1\" id=\"mmrc5\">3</span><span class=\"multexample1\" id=\"mmrc4\">6</span><span class=\"multexample1\" id=\"mmrc3\">0 </span></center></p><p class=\"desc\">Calculation 2: Multiplying 18 by 20.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "The result, 360, shows that the civil year initially used did not match the actual length of a solar year. Mesoamerican cultures recognized this discrepancy and added a 5-day period called *Wayeb* or *Winik* (<htcite0>; <htcite1>). A possible example of their astronomical advancements is the Group E. These buildings were not yet been fully understood (<htcite2>). However, some studies suggest that they may have been used to measure the seasons of the year (<htcite3>; <htcite4>).",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "ad11b3b2-8cdf-4d71-9cb7-2ac241850945",
                     "text": "Casares Contreras, Orlando & Cetina, José & Cabrera, Venus Sarahí.",
                     "page": "pp. 33 - 34",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2022",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "eca99877-c520-4569-a71c-0a5b3dd77dc4",
                     "text": "Casares Contreras, Orlando & Cetina, José & Cabrera, Venus Sarahí.",
                     "page": "pp. 33 - 34",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2022",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "8ecdaf57-d55d-4d95-bad5-f76e0f671483",
                     "text": "Šprajc, I.",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2021",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "e7c7458b-0c63-4485-9c7b-4640edcd9122",
                     "text": "Inomata, T.",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2017",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "dfab6e33-fe94-4aec-8d9b-ed02ca8402c8",
                     "text": "Martz de la Vega, H.",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2021",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p class=\"desc\"><iframe src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/UBMUR-3hHz0?si=mn22_mrWLJ23ueeO\" title=\"YouTube video player\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen style=\"aspect-ratio: 16 / 9; width: 55% !important;\"></iframe><br />Video 1: Group E Complex at Caracol, Belize. Recorded during a site visit on <htdate0>.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": [
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "2015",
                     "month": "4",
                     "day": "26"
                  }
               ],
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "#### Synchronization of the Calendars\n\nBecause the *Tzolkin* and *Haab* calendars have different durations, they only realign after 52 civil years (365 days each) or 73 ceremonial cycles (260 days each) (<htcite0>; <htcite1>).",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "ad11b3b2-8cdf-4d71-9cb7-2ac241850945",
                     "text": "Casares Contreras, Orlando & Cetina, José & Cabrera, Venus Sarahí.",
                     "page": "pp. 35",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2022",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "eca99877-c520-4569-a71c-0a5b3dd77dc4",
                     "text": "Casares Contreras, Orlando & Cetina, José & Cabrera, Venus Sarahí.",
                     "page": "pp. 35",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2022",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 2: A New Begin</b><br /><br />How can we confirm that the calendars synchronize after 52 civil years or 73 ceremonial cycles?</div></div></center>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "The claim holds true because both periods yield the same total number of days:\n- 52 × 365 = 18.980 days.\n- 73 × 260 = 18.980 days.\n\nThus, the two calendars perfectly realign after this period.\n\nThe complexity of working with multiple calendars led cultures like the Aztecs to create artifacts such as the *Sun Stone* (<htcite0>).",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "b8661476-12b4-42db-8522-ad5101b75f75",
                     "text": "Ocampo, Estela; Bidon-Chanal, Carlos",
                     "page": "pp. 175-176",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p class=\"desc\"><img id=\"imgd700\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgd700', '0%')\" src=\"images/MexicoCityMuseo/Cuauhxicalli.jpg\" class=\"imgcenter\"/>Figure 2: Aztec Sun Stone on display at the National Museum of Anthropology in Mexico City (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('0be2ea18-ab78-4cb1-b3be-1ff0ba4ade95'); return false;\">Museo Nacional de Antropologia - México</a> ; <a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('f023ffd4-7942-42d5-81e8-146da4491bef'); return false;\">INAH - MX, <span class=\"htdate\"></span></a>).<br />Photo taken on <htdate0> during a visit to the Museum.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": [
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "2016",
                     "month": "10",
                     "day": "21"
                  }
               ],
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "In this image, we observe the representation of a divinity commonly associated with the Sun at the center. Surrounding this divinity, we see various circles and inscriptions that served to mark the passage of time.",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_order",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Numerical Orders\n\nWhile studying the table of ten (<htcite0>), we reviewed the concept of numerical orders and saw that we can break a number down into its orders. For example, the number 2025 can be rewritten in orders (units, tens, hundreds), which can be expressed as multiples of 10:",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "4ee22ab8-e17c-48a8-8289-c8538aba77bf",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Rereading",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p style=\"text-align=center\"><p><math display=\"block\"><mn>2025</mn><mo> = (</mo> <mn>2</mn> <mo>×</mo> <mn>1000</mn><mo>) + </mo>  <mo>(</mo> <mn>0</mn> <mo>×</mo> <mn>100</mn><mo>) + </mo> <mo>(</mo> <mn>2</mn> <mo>×</mo> <mn>10</mn><mo>) + </mo> <mo>(</mo> <mn>5</mn> <mo>×</mo> <mn>1</mn> <mo>)</mo> </math></p><p class=\"desc\">Calculation 3: Rewriting the number 2025 showing its numerical orders in base 10.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "If we were to rewrite the same number using the vigesimal system, it would look like this:",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p style=\"text-align=center\"><p><math display=\"block\"><mn>2025</mn><mo> = (</mo> <mn>5</mn> <mo>×</mo> <mn>400</mn><mo>) + </mo> <mo>(</mo> <mn>1</mn> <mo>×</mo> <mn>20</mn><mo>) + </mo> <mo>(</mo> <mn>5</mn> <mo>×</mo> <mn>1</mn> <mo>)</mo> </math></p><p class=\"desc\">Calculation 4: Rewriting the number 2025 showing its numerical orders in base 20.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
